# Commit message template — shown in your editor when you run: git commit
# Configured in ~/.gitconfig: [commit] template = ~/.gitmessage
#
# Lines starting with # are comments and will NOT appear in the final message.
# The blank line below the subject line is REQUIRED — git uses it to separate
# the subject from the body.
#
# HOW TO USE:
#   1. Replace the first line with your actual subject line
#   2. Delete the first line if you have nothing to write yet
#   3. Leave a blank line after the subject
#   4. Write the body if the change needs explanation
#   5. Save and close the editor — git creates the commit
#
# To skip the template for a quick commit:
#   git commit -m "fix(parser): handle null input"
#
# To edit the last commit message:
#   git commit --amend


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SUBJECT LINE — required, 72 characters maximum
# Format: type(scope): short description
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# BODY — optional, wrap at 72 characters
# Explain WHAT changed and WHY. The diff shows HOW.
# Leave a blank line between the subject and the body.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# FOOTER — optional
# Closes #123       (closes a GitHub/GitLab issue)
# BREAKING CHANGE: description of what breaks and how to migrate
# Co-authored-by: Name <email@example.com>
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────


# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# CONVENTIONAL COMMITS — REFERENCE
# https://www.conventionalcommits.org/
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# FORMAT:
#   type(scope): short description
#   │     │      │
#   │     │      └── Imperative mood. No capital. No period. Max 72 chars.
#   │     └───────── Optional. The part of the codebase affected.
#   └─────────────── Required. See types below.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# TYPES:
#
#   feat      — A new feature or capability
#               Example: feat(lexer): add support for string literals
#
#   fix       — A bug fix
#               Example: fix(alloc): free buffer on early return
#
#   docs      — Documentation changes only (comments, README, cheatsheets)
#               Example: docs(readme): add build instructions
#
#   style     — Formatting, whitespace, missing semicolons (no logic change)
#               Example: style(parser): remove trailing whitespace
#
#   refactor  — Code restructuring — no bug fixed, no feature added
#               Example: refactor(lexer): extract tokenise_string function
#
#   perf      — Performance improvement
#               Example: perf(sort): replace bubble sort with quicksort
#
#   test      — Adding or fixing tests
#               Example: test(stack): add edge case for empty pop
#
#   build     — Build system changes (Makefile, compiler flags, scripts)
#               Example: build(makefile): add -fsanitize=address to debug target
#
#   ci        — CI/CD configuration changes (.github/workflows/, etc.)
#               Example: ci: add valgrind step to test pipeline
#
#   chore     — Maintenance that does not affect source or tests
#               Example: chore: add .DS_Store to .gitignore
#
#   revert    — Reverts a previous commit
#               Example: revert: revert "feat(parser): add UTF-8 support"
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SCOPE EXAMPLES (adjust to your project):
#
#   (parser)   (lexer)    (memory)   (utils)
#   (stack)    (list)     (alloc)    (io)
#   (makefile) (readme)   (tests)    (config)
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# SUBJECT LINE RULES:
#
#   ✓ Use imperative mood:  "add feature"  not  "added feature"
#   ✓ Start after colon with lowercase:  "fix(x): handle null"
#   ✓ No period at the end
#   ✓ Maximum 72 characters
#   ✓ Be specific: what does this commit do?
#
#   ✗ "fix bug"       — too vague
#   ✗ "WIP"           — incomplete
#   ✗ "update stuff"  — meaningless
#   ✗ "asdfgh"        — please no
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# BODY RULES:
#
#   Write the body when the subject line is not enough to understand the change.
#   Ask yourself:
#     Why was this change necessary?
#     What problem did it solve?
#     What side effects does it have?
#     What alternatives were considered?
#
#   Wrap at 72 characters.
#   Use blank lines between paragraphs.
#   Use "- " bullet points for lists.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# BREAKING CHANGES:
#
#   Method 1 — add ! after type/scope:
#     feat!: redesign the token API
#     feat(parser)!: change return type of parse() from int to t_result
#
#   Method 2 — add footer:
#     BREAKING CHANGE: parse() now returns t_result instead of int.
#     Callers must update to check result.error instead of the return value.
#
#   Use both for clarity.
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# COMPLETE EXAMPLES:
#
#   ── Simple fix ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#   fix(alloc): free temporary buffer before returning error
#
#   ── Feature with body ─────────────────────────────────────────
#   feat(parser): add support for nested function calls
#
#   The previous parser only handled function calls at the top level.
#   Nested calls like f(g(x)) would fail with a syntax error.
#
#   The fix adds a recursive descent step for argument expressions,
#   allowing arbitrary nesting depth up to the stack limit.
#
#   ── Breaking change ───────────────────────────────────────────
#   feat(token)!: replace char* with t_token struct in lexer API
#
#   The lexer previously returned raw char* pointers, which made it
#   impossible to carry type information alongside the value.
#
#   BREAKING CHANGE: ft_lexer_next() now returns t_token* instead of char*.
#   Callers must update to access token->value for the string content
#   and token->type for the token classification.
#
# ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════